@alex-melnyk this works except when the device is then rotated... 
I changed this slightly to use:

`aspectRatio: min(1 / MediaQuery.of(context).size.aspectRatio, _controller!.value.aspectRatio),`

which gives better values for my initial testing on Android - although iPhone sees different results again and it's now rotated when it wasn't before. 

@camsim99 - I feel that it might be better to look at this differently - the camera package should NOT try to correct the rotation at all. Only in CameraPreview widget - where you could do something like the above since this is a widget you're actually displaying. 

The user has the orientation information and aspect ratio to in theory properly handle this if they choose to do so differently. However I don't know what effect this will have on the "saved" images as there's 2 sides to this of course. The above thread has been rather unhelpfully littered with comments about the other side (the saved image) but this case should handle the preview.

Update on above, the rotation is only required on Android. 

```
return RotatedBox(
      quarterTurns: Platform.isAndroid ? (_controller!.description.sensorOrientation / 90).toInt() : 0,
      child: AspectRatio(
        aspectRatio: Platform.isAndroid
            ? min(1 / MediaQuery.of(context).size.aspectRatio, _controller!.value.aspectRatio)
            : MediaQuery.of(context).size.aspectRatio,
        child: CameraPreview(
          _controller!,
        ),
      ),
    );
```

@camsim99 this makes me think however there may be an issue on the iOS side too? My iPhone reports a sensor orientation of 90 degrees but the preview is already correctly oriented. This then gives us different behaviour between Android and iOS - one of them has to be wrong.

@michaelnabil230 what is the result in your app? Which versions of camera / camerax are you using? 

Just saying it doesn't work doesn't really help identify the problem - which is something still eluding us. 

Perhaps you could also let us know the values being reported by your camera for the sensorOrientation - that might give some more information. 

@camsim99 just to add again - I got the customer who initially reported the issue to me to test the above fix and he confirmed it worked too - that was a horizontal oriented tablet which was one of the more elusive issues we were trying to work out and it's the first time I've had it working properly on all of my devices and his.

I’m investigating the rotation behavior and noticed that if I change the `_getQuarterTurns()` function from:
```
 int _getQuarterTurns() {
    final Map<DeviceOrientation, int> turns = <DeviceOrientation, int>{
      DeviceOrientation.portraitUp: 0,
      DeviceOrientation.landscapeRight: 1,
      DeviceOrientation.portraitDown: 2,
      DeviceOrientation.landscapeLeft: 3,
    };
    return turns[_getApplicableOrientation()]!;
  }
```

to:
```
int _getQuarterTurns() {
    final Map<DeviceOrientation, int> turns = <DeviceOrientation, int>{
      DeviceOrientation.portraitUp: 3,
      DeviceOrientation.landscapeRight: 2,
      DeviceOrientation.portraitDown: 1,
      DeviceOrientation.landscapeLeft: 0,
    };
    return turns[_getApplicableOrientation()]!;
  }
```

the rotation appears both normal and mirrored. This change alters how the device’s orientation is mapped to the rotation applied. I'm trying to check in native, but it seems a bit confusing to me.

Works to front camera.

> > CameraController listens to rotation changes, but it doesn't check what the current rotation is before that, and never sets target rotations _except_ when the rotation _changes_. This seems like it _may_ be a bug, but I'm not sure. It would explain why the orientation is off when switching cameras, unless you go out of your way to rotate a particular way and back.
> > See: https://cs.android.com/androidx/platform/frameworks/support/+/85c1df12ff3922d950cb00a08533fa66c30f4aa4:camera/camera-view/src/main/java/androidx/camera/view/CameraController.java;l=399-403

@t-m-w Ack. I'll check out how the target rotation of the preview may play into this issue,

@camsim99 the rotation issue has been reported to me today by a colleague. I can see you've got a PR for that, tyvm.

However, on Android 12 the image is in black & white in addition to the rotation. On Android 13 it's full colour with rotation. 

We didn't have either issue until a recent update, so any idea if these issues are linked? If not I can get some info together and open a new issue.

@darshankawar I'm also getting the similar issue on Samsung Galaxy S20, Android 13 after upgrading `camera` version to "0.11.1" and `camera_android_camerax` to "0.6.13". It was not occurring before on any of the devices that I have.

Issue Screenshot:
<img src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c071f78a-edd8-4d0f-9821-f07ccb47c1ba" width ="300">

@camsim99 Thank you for working on this fix. This definitely is working on my Samsung Tab S9 FE+ device, but still doesn't appear to be working on my MicroTouch display.

Other than it running Android 13, what else can I provide to help debug what's happening?

If I understand the underlying issue correctly, it has to do with the reported rotation of the camera?

@kylehayes It likely has to do with how your device provides `Surface`s to the camera plugin. It's possible that the API we use to detect if your device needs the preview rotation correction is not reporting the right value for the MicroTouch display.

I haven't seen this on any of my devices, so it would be difficult for me to debug, but if you're willing to help, you could run a local version of the `camera_android_camerax` plugin and play around with the value of `_handlesCropAndRotation` here: https://github.com/flutter/packages/blob/main/packages/camera/camera_android_camerax/lib/src/android_camera_camerax.dart#L847. I wonder if we are building one preview `Widget` on that device when we should building another. We'd expect `_handlesCropAndRotation` to be `false` on Android 13 devices, for context, but maybe something that we don't expect is happening.

If you need help doing that, let me know!

@camsim99 I will do some more testing in the coming days - it seems to me a bit more of a unique problem to my setup than a flaw in the package. it's also not strictly related to this issue, I thought it was initially the rotation not being handled until I saw the flash reference, hence I deleted my original comment. 

If I think it's something could / should be handled better I'll file a separate issue no worries. 

In good news - the customer who reported the original issue has confirmed that the new fix works correctly for them without my manual fix which I previously applied so I would confirm this is solved :)

